Goring by Sea, Sussex, England":"Goring by Sea, Sussex, England"},"en":{"1440–1481":"1440–1481","1439–1484":"1439–1484","1452–1529":"1452–1529","1457–1543":"1457–1543","1457":"1457","1455":"1455","1543":"1543","1452":"1452","1440":"1440","1484":"1484","1460":"1460","1481":"1481","1529":"1529","1439":"1439","Laughton, Sussex, England":"Laughton, Sussex, England","Isle of Wight, Hampshire, England":"Isle of Wight, Hampshire, England","Trotton with Chithurst, Chichester, Sussex, England":"Chichester, Sussex, England","Trotton, Sussex, England":"Trotton, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Goring by Sea, Sussex, England":"Goring by Sea, Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pelham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Sussex): habitational name from Brent Pelham, Furneux Pelham, and Stocking Pelham in Hertfordshire, so called from the Old English personal name <i>Pēola</i> + <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’. Compare   Pellham  .","History: The manor of Pelham in Hertfordshire, England, was held by Walter de Pelham in the reign of Edward I (1272–1307). His descendants became constables of Pevensey Castle, Sussex, and were so influential that their badge, the buckle, is seen in at least eleven of the county's churches, and as a decoration on iron chimney-backs in Sussex farmhouses. Various branches of the family were ennobled and their titles include earl of Chichester and earl of Yarborough. The family also once held the dukedom of Newcastle and the marquessate of Clare. Peter Pelham (born <i>c.</i> 1695), an engraver, emigrated to Boston, MA, after 1728, and was stepfather to the artist John Singleton Copley."],"variants":[{"name":"Pellum","meanings":["English: variant of   Pelham  ."]},{"name":"Pellham","meanings":["Altered form of English   Pelham  ."]}]},{"name":"Katharine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Katherine  , associated by folk etymology with Greek <i>katharos</i> ‘pure’. This is the preferred spelling in Germany. It is also the one used in the name of the American film star  Katharine Hepburn  (  1907–2003 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Katherine","meanings":["Variant of   Katherine ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":15,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Katharine Pelham was born in 1440, in Laughton, Sussex, England. She married Sir Thomas Lewknor in 1460, in Trotton, Sussex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1481, in Isle of Wight, Hampshire, England, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1440–1481":"1440–1481","1439–1484":"1439–1484","1452–1529":"1452–1529","1457–1543":"1457–1543","1457":"1457","1455":"1455","1543":"1543","1452":"1452","1440":"1440","1484":"1484","1460":"1460","1481":"1481","1529":"1529","1439":"1439","Laughton, Sussex, England":"Laughton, Sussex, England","Isle of Wight, Hampshire, England":"Isle of Wight, Hampshire, England","Trotton with Chithurst, Chichester, Sussex, England":"Chichester, Sussex, England","Trotton, Sussex, England":"Trotton, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Goring by Sea, Sussex, England":"Goring by Sea, Sussex, England"},"fi":{"1440–1481":"1440–1481","1439–1484":"1439–1484","1452–1529":"1452–1529","1457–1543":"1457–1543","1457":"1457","1455":"1455","1543":"1543","1452":"1452","1440":"1440","1484":"1484","1460":"1460","1481":"1481","1529":"1529","1439":"1439","Laughto